I started working remotely in 2021, initially as a temporary arrangement. Five years later, I can't imagine going back to an office full-time. But remote work isn't automatically better—it requires intentional practices to work well.

## Communication is Everything

In an office, communication happens organically. Remote work requires deliberate effort.

### Over-communicate by Default
When in doubt, share more context. What seems obvious to you isn't obvious to someone who can't see your screen or overhear your conversations.

### Async First, Sync When Needed
Default to asynchronous communication (messages, documents, recorded videos), and reserve synchronous time (meetings, calls) for discussions that truly benefit from real-time interaction.

### Write Everything Down
Decisions made in calls should be documented. Context shared verbally should be written down. Your future self (and your teammates) will thank you.

## Boundaries Matter More Than You Think

The biggest challenge of remote work isn't productivity—it's the blurring of work and life.

### Create Physical Separation
If possible, have a dedicated workspace. When you leave that space, you're done working.

### Set Clear Working Hours
Communicate your availability and protect your off-hours. Flexibility is a benefit of remote work, not an obligation to be always available.

### End Your Day Intentionally
Without a commute to mark the transition, create your own ritual. I take a walk around my neighborhood to mentally close out the workday.

## Building Culture Remotely

The hardest part of distributed teams is maintaining culture and connection.

### Regular Video Check-ins
Weekly one-on-ones and team meetings with cameras on help maintain personal connections. Not every meeting needs video, but regular face time matters.

### Virtual Social Events
They're awkward at first, but optional social calls, game sessions, or virtual coffee chats build relationships that make work better.

### Celebrate Wins Publicly
Without hallway conversations, good work can go unnoticed. Make recognition visible and frequent.

## Productivity Tactics That Work

### Time Blocking
Schedule focused work blocks and protect them. My most productive hours are blocked for deep work with notifications silenced.

### The Two-Minute Rule
If a task takes less than two minutes, do it immediately. Small tasks pile up and create mental overhead.

### Regular Breaks
The Pomodoro Technique (25 minutes focused, 5 minutes break) keeps me sharp throughout the day.

## What I Miss About Offices

Remote work isn't perfect. I miss:
- Spontaneous whiteboard sessions
- Learning by osmosis from nearby conversations
- The energy of working alongside others

The key is acknowledging these trade-offs while maximizing the benefits of remote flexibility.

## Final Thoughts

Remote work isn't inherently better or worse than office work—it's different. Success requires adapting your habits, communication style, and expectations.

For me, the flexibility to design my own environment and schedule outweighs what I've given up. But it took intentional effort to make it work.
